## BETTER APPROACH
**Explanation:** 
Use a recursive approach. The sum of digits of $N$ is the last digit (`n % 10`) plus the sum of digits of the remaining number (`n / 10`). This is elegant but uses stack space.

**Time Complexity:** O(log₁₀ N) - proportional to the number of digits.
**Space Complexity:** O(log₁₀ N) due to the recursive call stack.

```cpp
int sumOfDigitsRecursive(int n) {
    if (n < 0) n = -n;
    if (n == 0) return 0;
    return (n % 10) + sumOfDigitsRecursive(n / 10);
}
```

---

## OPTIMAL APPROACH
**Explanation:** 
Use an iterative loop with modulo and division operators. This is the most memory-efficient way because it uses constant space and avoids the overhead of recursion or string conversion. We extract the last digit using `% 10` and remove it using `/ 10` until the number becomes zero.

**Time Complexity:** O(log₁₀ N)
**Space Complexity:** O(1)

```cpp
int sumOfDigitsOptimal(int n) {
