## PROBLEM UNDERSTANDING
The goal is to print a **Hollow Half Pyramid** of size `n`. 
A hollow half pyramid has stars along:
1. The first column (`col == 0`).
2. The last row (`row == n-1`).
3. The diagonal where the row meets the column (`row == col`).
Your provided code is logic-wise correct for the conditions, but it could be optimized slightly in terms of loop boundaries to avoid unnecessary checks.

---

## BRUTE FORCE APPROACH
**Explanation:** 
Iterate through every cell of an $n \times n$ grid. For every cell `(row, col)`, check if it lies on the boundary of the half pyramid. If it does, print a star; otherwise, print a space.
**Time Complexity:** $O(n^2)$
**Space Complexity:** $O(1)$

```cpp
void bruteForceHollowHalfPyramid(int n) {
    for (int row = 0; row < n; row++) {
        for (int col = 0; col < n; col++) {
            // Checks every single cell in an n x n square
            if (col == 0 || row == n - 1 || row == col) {
                cout << "* ";
            } else {
                cout << "  ";
            }
        }
        cout << endl;
    }
}
```

---

## BETTER APPROACH
**Explanation:** 
Instead of iterating through the full $n \times n$ grid, we limit the inner loop to only go up to the current row index (`col <= row`). This significantly reduces the number of "else" space prints and iterations.
**Time Complexity:** $O(n^2)$ (specifically $n(n+1)/2$ iterations)
**Space Complexity:** $O(1)$

```cpp
void betterHollowHalfPyramid(int n) {
    for (int row = 0; row < n; row++) {
        // Inner loop only runs up to the current row
        for (int col = 0; col <= row; col++) {
            if (col == 0 || row == n - 1 || row == col) {
                cout << "* ";
            } else {
                cout << "  ";
            }
        }
        cout << endl;
    }
}
```

---

## OPTIMAL APPROACH
**Explanation:** 
While the time complexity remains $O(n^2)$, we can make the code more readable and use a specific case for the last row to avoid constant `if` checks inside the inner loop for that specific row. This is the standard way to implement pattern problems efficiently in a competitive programming context.
**Time Complexity:** $O(n^2)$
**Space Complexity:** $O(1)$

```cpp
void optimalHollowHalfPyramid(int n) {
    for (int row = 0; row < n; row++) {
        for (int col = 0; col <= row; col++) {
            // First column, Last row, or Hypotenuse (row == col)
            if (col == 0 || col == row || row == n - 1) {
                cout << "* ";
            } else {
                cout << "  ";
            }
        }
        cout << endl;
    }
}
```

