Your code is logically sound for a beginner, but it contains a standard C++ issue called **Variable Length Arrays (VLAs)**.

### The Main Issue: `int arr[n]`
In standard C++, the size of an array must be known at **compile time** (e.g., `int arr[100]`). Defining `int arr[n]` where `n` is a variable works in some compilers (like GCC) as an extension, but it is not standard C++ and can cause crashes if `n` is too large.

### Recommended Fixes

#### Option 1: Using `std::vector` (The "C++ way")
Vectors are dynamic arrays that handle memory for you. This is the industry standard.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector> // Required for vector
using namespace std;

void printArray(const vector<int>& arr) {
    for(int i = 0; i < arr.size(); i++) {
        cout << arr[i] << " ";
    }
    cout << endl;
}

int main() {
    int n;
    cout << "Enter the number of elements: ";
    cin >> n;

    vector<int> arr(n); // Creates a vector of size n
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        cout << "Enter element " << i + 1 << ": ";
        cin >> arr[i];
    }

    cout << "Your array is: ";
    printArray(arr);

    return 0;
}
```

#### Option 2: Dynamic Allocation (using `new`)
If you must use pointers/raw arrays:

```cpp
int n;
cin >> n;
int* arr = new int[n]; // Allocate memory on the heap

// ... use the array ...

delete[] arr; // Crucial: You must free the memory manually
```

